T1  - Modelling the process of job search
AU  - Narendranathan, Wiji
AU  - Nickell, Stephen
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 28
IS  - 1
SP  - 29
EP  - 49
PY  - 1985
DA  - 1985/04/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(85)90065-X
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030440768590065X
AB  - This paper is concerned with the specification and estimation of a genuinely structural but static model of individual search behaviour in which the estimated reservation wage actually satisfies the optimality condition. The identification of the parameters of interest is achieved by the a priori specification of the vacancy-wage distribution. The model is estimated using the data from the 1978–1979 D.H.S.S. Cohort Study of the Unemployed. The estimated parameters reflect, in the main, our prior views and generate a number of interesting results. In particular the elasticity of unemployment spell duration with respect to unemployment benefits is estimated to be around 0.18–0.26.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - State dependency in youth unemployment: A lost generation?
AU  - Lynch, Lisa M.
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 28
IS  - 1
SP  - 71
EP  - 84
PY  - 1985
DA  - 1985/04/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(85)90067-3
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407685900673
AB  - Utilizing a job search framework and survey data on both completed and uncompleted spells of unemployment we present in this paper maximum likelihood estimates of the determinants of re-employment probabilities of young workers in Britain. The model used allows us to examine the importance of state dependency in youth unemployment as well as ethnicity, educational qualifications, and unemployment income. Results suggest that there is strong evidence of negative duration dependence in the transition from unemployment to employment for young workers in Britain.
ER  - 

