TY  - JOUR
T1  - The duration of contract strikes in U.S. manufacturing
AU  - Kennan, John
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 28
IS  - 1
SP  - 5
EP  - 28
PY  - 1985
DA  - 1985/04/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(85)90064-8
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407685900648
AB  - This paper develops new evidence on the hazard function for strike duration, and on cyclical changes in this function, using data on contract strikes in U.S. manufacturing industries. A flexible duration model is estimated, and it is found that the hazard rate is generally a U-shaped function of strike age. The level of industrial production is found to have a significant positive effect on the hazard rate: strike duration is countercyclical. A convenient parametric model of heterogeneity and duration dependence is introduced, in which the logit of the hazard rate is a polynomial function of strike age, up to a random individual effect drawn from a beta distribution. Estimates of this ‘beta-logit’ model indicate that it is difficult to detect the influence of unobserved heterogeneity on the aggregate hazard function for strike duration.
ER  - 

